- !<Text/d04c8cf3-f3ee-4025-9a83-647dbf41d2c2>
  PrefabRemaps:
    []
  Name: Text
  Enabled: true
  RenderOrder: 0
  StretchMode: Stretch
  VerticalAlignment: Center
  HorizontalAlignment: Left
  MeshShadowMode: None
  ShadowColor: {x: 1.000000, y: 1.000000, z: 1.000000, w: 1.000000}
  ShadowDensity: 1.000000
  Text: |-
    This test assesses fine motor control by asking the patient to rapidly tap the index finger and thumb together. 
    It is used to evaluate bradykinesia in Parkinson’s disease, focusing not only on speed but also on movement size,
    rhythm, and how performance changes over a short period.
    Ask the patient to tap as quickly and as widely as possible for about 10–15 seconds.
    Observe for slowing, reduced amplitude, irregular rhythm, hesitation in starting, or fatigue over time, 
    as well as differences between hands. 
    Score based on overall impairment and the presence of interruptions or progressive decline.
